  "preFix": {
    "title": "Boulangere potatoes",
    "subtitle": "Thinly sliced, slow-baked in stock",
    "excerpt": "Potatoes sliced thin and layered with onions, then baked in stock until absorbed and the top is golden. The classic alternative to dauphinoise without the cream.",
    "sourceNotes": "French technique, pommes boulangere, adopted into British cooking. Originally baked under a joint of meat so the potatoes cooked in its drippings. Eliza Acton referenced similar methods.",
    "body": {
      "type": "doc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Boulangere potatoes are the leaner, equally satisfying sibling of dauphinoise. The stock soaks into the potato slices as it reduces, leaving them tender and flavourful rather than rich. The top layer crisps and browns in the oven while the layers underneath stay moist.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "What you need",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "ingredientsList",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "name": "Potato",
                "unit": "g",
                "amount": 1200,
                "prepNote": "Maris Piper or King Edward, peeled and very thinly sliced",
                "groupLabel": null,
                "isOptional": false,
                "ingredientId": "cmp49f5fz004drkv4xvm4u4jd",
                "ingredientSlug": "potato"
              },
